    "summary": "The Battle of Zama (202 BC) was the decisive final engagement of the [[event:1054|Second Punic War]], in which the Roman general Scipio Africanus defeated Hannibal Barca's army on North African soil, forcing Carthage to accept humiliating peace terms and ending Carthaginian power in the western Mediterranean. It was the only major battle of Hannibal's career that he lost.\n\nScipio had spent years studying and adapting Hannibal's own tactics, and at Zama he faced the problem of Hannibal's war elephants — eighty of them — head-on. He trained his legions to open lanes in the formation to let the elephants pass harmlessly through, negating their shock value. His Numidian cavalry ally Masinissa, who had defected from Carthage to Rome, proved decisive: the Roman and Numidian cavalry routed Carthaginian cavalry and then returned to encircle Hannibal's infantry from the rear — essentially replicating the [[event:1056|Battle of Cannae]] encirclement against its own architect.\n\nHannibal, recognizing defeat, escaped and later urged Carthage to accept peace terms. The treaty that followed stripped Carthage of all overseas possessions, its navy, and its war elephants, required a massive fifty-year indemnity, and forbade Carthage from making war without Roman permission. Scipio was given the honorific 'Africanus' for his triumph. Though Carthage recovered economically, the peace terms left it permanently vulnerable — a vulnerability exploited in the [[event:1058|Third Punic War]] half a century later.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Zama",
